Secure Data Storage, Secure Data Transmission and Digital Signature using GnuPG
Date:


AIM
To demonstrate secure data storage, secure data transmission, and creation &
verification of digital signatures using the GnuPG cryptographic tool. ALGORITHM
STEP 1: Start Kali Linux in VMware.

STEP 2: Secure Data Storage
	•	Create a confidential file
	•	Encrypt the file using symmetric encryption
	•	Decrypt the file to retrieve original data STEP 3: Secure Data Transmission
	•	Generate public and private key pair
	•	Encrypt data using receiver’s public key
	•	Decrypt data using receiver’s private key STEP 4: Digital Signature
	•	Digitally sign a message using private key
	•	Verify the digital signature using public key

CODING:
PART A – Secure Data Storage (Symmetric Encryption) Step 1: Create a File
Command:
nano secret.txt
Content:
This is confidential data

Step 2: Encrypt the File Command:
gpg -c secret.txt
Sample Output:

Enter passphrase: Repeat passphrase:
Encrypted file created as:

secret.txt.gpg

Step 3: Decrypt the File Command:
gpg secret.txt.gpg
Sample Output:
Enter passphrase:
gpg: AES256 encrypted data

Step 4: Verify Decrypted File Command:
cat secret.txt
Sample Output:

This is confidential data

PART B – Secure Data Transmission (Asymmetric Encryption) Step 1: Generate GPG Key Pair
Command:
gpg --full-generate-key
Sample Output (Selections):
Please select key type: RSA and RSA Key size: 2048
Key created successfully

Step 2: List Generated Keys Command:
gpg --list-keys
Sample Output:
pub rsa2048 2026-01-31 [SC]
uid Student <student@example.com>


Step 3: Encrypt File Using Public Key Command:
gpg -e -r "Student" secret.txt Sample Output: secret.txt.gpg created
Step 4: Decrypt File Using Private Key Command:
gpg -d secret.txt.gpg > decrypted.txt
Sample Output:

gpg: encrypted with 2048-bit RSA key


Step 5: Verify Decrypted Data Command:
cat decrypted.txt
Sample Output:
This is confidential data

PART C – Digital Signature Creation & Verification Step 1: Create Message File
Command:

nano message.txt
Content:

This message is digitally signed

Step 2: Create Digital Signature Command:
gpg --sign message.txt
Sample Output:
Enter passphrase:
message.txt.gpg created

Step 3: Verify Digital Signature Command:
gpg --verify message.txt.gpg
Sample Output:

Good signature from "Student <student@example.com>"

